SIMPLE: spool
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spool
<hw>Spool</hw> <pr>(sp⟦oomac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>spole</ets>, OD. <ets>spoele</ets>, D. <ets>spoel</ets>; akin to G.
<ets>spule</ets>, OHG. <ets>spuola</ets>, Dan. & Sw.
<ets>spole</ets>.]</ety> <def>A piece of cane or reed with a knot at
each end, or a hollow cylinder of wood with a ridge at each end, used to
wind thread or yarn upon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Spool stand</b></col>, <cd>an article holding spools of
thread, turning on pins, -- used by women at their work.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spool</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spool
<hw>Spool</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spooled</conjf> <pr>(sp⟦oomac⟧ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Spooling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To wind on a spool or
spools.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spooler</ent>⟦br⟧
